  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Can European citizens live and work in the Bahamas?",
  "response": "European citizens can live and work in the Bahamas, but they must follow the country's immigration laws and regulations. Here are some key points to consider:\n\n1. **Visa Requirements**: European citizens typically need a visa to enter the Bahamas. The type of visa required depends on the purpose and duration of the stay. For short visits (up to 90 days), a tourist visa is usually sufficient. For longer stays or for work purposes, a different type of visa or a work permit is required.\n\n2. **Work Permits**: To work in the Bahamas, European citizens need to obtain a work permit. The employer usually sponsors the work permit application, and the process can take several weeks to a few months. The availability of work permits can be limited, and priority is often given to Bahamian citizens.\n\n3. **Residency**: For those looking to live in the Bahamas long-term, options include applying for permanent residency or an annual residence permit. Permanent residency is challenging to obtain and typically requires a significant investment or family ties to the Bahamas.\n\n4. **Real Estate and Investment**: Some European citizens choose to invest in real estate in the Bahamas, which can facilitate the process of obtaining residency. The Bahamas offers the option of the Annual or Permanent Residence through investment in real estate.\n\n5. **Healthcare and Other Services**: European citizens should also consider healthcare, education, and other services when planning to live in the Bahamas. While the country offers good services, they may differ from what is available in Europe.\n\nIt is advisable to consult with the Bahamian embassy or consulate in your home country, or a qualified immigration lawyer, to get the most up-to-date and specific advice tailored to your situation.",
